[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 12.7: Vital Sign Trajectory Monitoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium-Complex · **Phase:** Clinical Integration · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.15-0.40 per patient-hour (streaming)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A patient's heart rate has been creeping up by 3-4 beats per minute every hour for the last six hours. Their blood pressure is trending downward, slowly but consistently. Neither value has crossed any threshold. Neither has triggered a single alarm. The nurse checks vitals every four hours, glances at the numbers, sees "within normal limits," and moves on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Six hours later, the patient is coding.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the trajectory problem. Clinical deterioration rarely announces itself with a single abnormal reading. It whispers through gradual trends, subtle slope changes, and coordinated shifts across multiple parameters that individually look unremarkable. The Modified Early Warning Score (MEWS) and National Early Warning Score (NEWS) attempt to capture this by combining single-point-in-time measurements into a composite score. But they're snapshots. They tell you "right now this patient scores a 4." They don't tell you "this patient scored a 2 yesterday, a 3 this morning, and a 4 now, and that trajectory has a very specific signature we've seen before."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The human body doesn't deteriorate in step functions. It deteriorates in curves. And the shape of that curve carries more information than any single point on it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In ICU settings, studies have documented that clinical deterioration is often identifiable 6 to 12 hours before a rapid response event when you look at trajectory rather than threshold. On general medical floors, the gap is even larger because monitoring is less frequent and the staff-to-patient ratio is worse. The Institute for Healthcare Improvement has highlighted that failure to recognize and respond to clinical deterioration remains one of the most common causes of preventable inpatient deaths.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The technology to watch these trajectories continuously exists. It's a time series problem. But a time series problem with some very specific constraints that make it meaningfully different from, say, predicting tomorrow's stock price.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Time Series Trajectory Analysis for Physiological Signals
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What We Mean by "Trajectory"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A vital sign trajectory is the shape of a patient's vital sign measurements over time. Not just the current value, not just whether it's above or below a threshold, but the pattern of change: the slope, the acceleration, the variability, the correlations between different parameters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Think of it this way. If heart rate is 95, that's information. If heart rate was 72 yesterday and is 95 now, that's more information. If heart rate has been climbing steadily at 3 bpm per hour for the last eight hours while blood pressure has been declining at 2 mmHg per hour, that's a story. And it's a story that experienced clinicians recognize as a sepsis signature even before either value crosses a traditional alarm threshold.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Trajectory monitoring captures that story computationally.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Building Blocks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-specific baselines.** The most critical concept in vital sign trajectory monitoring is that "normal" is different for every patient. A resting heart rate of 90 might be alarming for an athletic 25-year-old. It might be completely unremarkable for a 70-year-old with chronic heart failure who's been running at 88-92 for the last three days. Any trajectory system that uses population-based norms exclusively will drown you in false alerts. You need to establish each patient's individual baseline from their own recent history, then measure deviation from their normal, not from some textbook number.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trend decomposition.** Raw vital sign data is noisy. A blood pressure reading bounces around even in stable patients due to measurement variability, patient movement, cuff positioning, and a dozen other sources of non-clinical variation. Effective trajectory systems decompose the signal into components: the underlying trend (slowly moving baseline), periodic components (circadian rhythm, medication cycles), and residual noise. The trend component is what you're watching for deterioration. The residual is what you're trying to ignore.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Slope estimation.** Once you have a denoised trend, you're computing the rate of change (first derivative) and the acceleration of change (second derivative). A patient whose heart rate slope has been zero and suddenly becomes positive is more concerning than a patient whose heart rate has always had a slight upward drift. Second-derivative changes (the slope is steepening) are particularly interesting because they suggest the clinical process is accelerating.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-variate correlation.** Vital signs don't move independently. The body's compensatory mechanisms create predictable correlations. Early sepsis, for example, often shows rising heart rate and rising respiratory rate before blood pressure drops. Heart failure decompensation shows a specific pattern of weight gain, oxygen saturation decline, and heart rate increase. Tracking coordinated movement across multiple parameters increases sensitivity and specificity compared to monitoring each parameter in isolation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Changepoint detection.** Sometimes the trajectory doesn't gradually drift. It shifts. A patient's baseline blood pressure was 120/80 for three days, and now it's 105/70. That's a level shift, not a trend. Changepoint detection algorithms identify these abrupt changes in the statistical properties of the time series. In clinical contexts, a changepoint often represents a new clinical state: the onset of bleeding, a medication taking effect, or a physiological compensation mechanism engaging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why This Is Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let me be straight about the failure modes, because this is one of those problems where the engineering isn't the hard part. The clinical integration is.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Alert fatigue.** This is the existential threat to any monitoring system. Nurses on a typical medical-surgical floor already dismiss 85-95% of physiological alarms as clinically irrelevant (this statistic has been reproduced across multiple studies). If your trajectory system adds another layer of alerts that are mostly noise, clinical staff will ignore it within a week. You have to be specific enough to matter. A system that fires 50 trajectory alerts per shift and 2 of them are clinically significant is a failed system, even though those 2 were genuinely important. The signal-to-noise ratio is everything.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Artifact vs. real change.** Patient moves in bed, blood pressure cuff auto-inflates and gets a bad read, pulse oximeter probe slips off a finger for 30 seconds. These all look like acute changes in the raw data. Your system needs to distinguish between physiological reality and measurement artifact. This is harder than it sounds. A sudden SpO2 drop from 97% to 82% could be a probe coming loose (common, harmless) or acute desaturation (rare, life-threatening). Context matters: did it recover within 30 seconds? Did other parameters move simultaneously? Is this a known motion-artifact pattern?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication effects.** A patient receives a beta-blocker, and their heart rate drops 15 bpm over the next hour. That's not deterioration; that's the drug working. Your trajectory system needs to be aware of medication administration events, or it will generate alerts for every expected pharmacological response. This means integrating with the medication administration record (MAR), which means your "simple" time series system now depends on a clinical data interface that's anything but simple.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Intermittent vs. continuous data.** In an ICU with continuous bedside monitoring, you might get a heart rate reading every second. On a general medical floor, you get vital signs every four hours (or every 8, depending on acuity). Trajectory estimation from 4-hour intervals is fundamentally different from trajectory estimation from continuous data. You're interpolating between sparse points with much wider confidence intervals. A system designed for ICU-density data will not work on floor-density data without significant architectural changes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical actionability.** "This patient's trajectory is concerning" is not actionable. Clinical staff need specificity: What parameters are moving? In what direction? How does this compare to known deterioration signatures? What's the recommended response? A vague "patient score increasing" notification is worse than useless because it interrupts workflow without guiding action.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The State of the Art
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Early warning scores (MEWS, NEWS, NEWS2) are the current clinical standard for detecting deterioration. They work by assigning point values to individual vital sign readings based on how far they deviate from normal ranges, then summing the points. They've been validated extensively and do improve outcomes when implemented with appropriate escalation protocols.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Where they fall short is exactly the trajectory problem. NEWS evaluates a single point in time. A patient could have a NEWS score of 3 at two consecutive measurements (safe enough that no escalation is triggered), while the trajectory from measurement to measurement represents a clinically significant deterioration that a more sophisticated analysis would catch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Research systems have demonstrated that adding trend features (slopes, changes from prior readings, trajectory statistics) to early warning models improves the prediction of rapid response events by 15-30% compared to snapshot-only models, depending on the patient population and the event being predicted. TODO: Verify this range against specific published studies; common citation is Churpek et al. and similar deterioration prediction research.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenge isn't building the model. It's deploying it in a way that clinical staff trust, that integrates into workflow, and that doesn't make the alert fatigue problem worse.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Vital Sign Sources] → [Ingestion / Streaming] → [Patient State Engine] → [Trajectory Analysis] → [Alert Logic] → [Clinical Display]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Vital Sign Sources.** Bedside monitors (continuous), nurse-documented observations (intermittent), wearable devices (variable frequency), medication administration records (event-driven). Different sources have different reliability characteristics and different latencies. The architecture must handle heterogeneous input frequencies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Ingestion / Streaming.** A streaming layer that can receive high-frequency data (continuous monitors), low-frequency data (nursing assessments), and event data (medication administration) into a unified patient timeline. Must handle late-arriving data, out-of-order events, and corrections.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient State Engine.** Maintains a rolling model of each patient's current physiological state: their recent baselines, their expected ranges, their current trend components. This is stateful computation: you need to remember what "normal" looks like for this specific patient over the last 24-72 hours. The state engine must handle patient admission (no baseline yet), transfers (new context), and post-procedure periods (expected disruption).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trajectory Analysis.** Computes trend statistics from the patient state: slope of each vital sign, cross-parameter correlations, deviation from baseline, changepoints. This is where the actual math lives. The output is a set of trajectory features that describe the shape of the patient's recent physiological history.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Alert Logic.** Translates trajectory features into clinical decisions: suppress (normal variation), watch (mild concern, increase monitoring), alert (escalate to nursing), alarm (immediate clinical attention needed). The alert logic must be tunable per unit, per acuity level, and ideally per patient population. A cardiac step-down unit has very different alert thresholds than a post-surgical floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical Display.** The trajectory information reaches the clinical team through some interface: a dashboard, an in-EHR notification, a pager alert, a change to the patient's displayed status on the unit board. The display must show what's happening, why the system flagged it, and what the recommended next step is. Pure numbers without context will be ignored.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for vital sign ingestion.** Vital sign data from bedside monitors and nursing assessments arrives continuously and needs to be processed with low latency. Kinesis Data Streams provides the durable, ordered, scalable streaming layer that can handle thousands of data points per second across hundreds of patients. Each patient gets a partition key, ensuring their readings are processed in order. The 24-hour (extendable to 365 days) retention means you can reprocess data if your analysis logic changes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for event-driven trajectory computation.** Each new vital sign reading triggers a trajectory update for that patient. Lambda handles the burst pattern well: quiet at 3am, heavy at shift-change assessment times. For floor patients with intermittent vitals, the invocation pattern is naturally sparse and Lambda's per-invocation pricing makes sense. For continuous monitoring scenarios with higher throughput, Kinesis Data Analytics (Apache Flink) is the alternative.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics (Apache Flink) for continuous stream processing.** For ICU-level continuous monitoring, the stream processing needs stateful windowed computations: rolling averages, slope estimates, cross-parameter correlations computed over sliding windows. Apache Flink (managed via Kinesis Data Analytics) handles stateful stream processing with exactly-once semantics. It maintains per-patient state without external database calls on every event.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for patient state storage.** Each patient's rolling baseline, current trajectory metrics, and alert history need to live in a low-latency store that can handle high write throughput. DynamoDB's single-digit millisecond reads and writes make it suitable for the stateful computations that reference and update patient state on every new reading. TTL support automatically ages out data for discharged patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Timestream for historical trajectory storage.** The full history of vital sign readings and computed trajectory metrics goes into a time series database optimized for temporal queries. Timestream handles the time-based retention tiers (hot data for recent trajectories, cold data for research and retrospective analysis) and supports the temporal query patterns (give me this patient's heart rate slope over the last 12 hours) natively.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SNS for alert routing.** When trajectory analysis produces an alert, it needs to reach the right person through the right channel. SNS handles fan-out to multiple subscribers: pager, EHR notification, nursing station dashboard, charge nurse summary. Topic-based routing allows different alert severities to reach different endpoints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for system health monitoring.** You're building a clinical safety system. You need to know immediately if the pipeline falls behind, if Lambda errors spike, if Kinesis is throttling, or if alert delivery latency exceeds acceptable bounds. CloudWatch alarms on processing latency, error rates, and alert delivery confirmation close the operational monitoring loop.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Bedside Monitors\nHL7/FHIR] -->|Continuous| B[Kinesis Data Streams\npatient-vitals]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C[Nursing Assessments\nEHR Events] -->|Intermittent| B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D[MAR Events\nMedication Admin] -->|Event-driven| B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Stream| E{Data Density?}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|ICU: Continuous| F[Kinesis Data Analytics\nApache Flink]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Floor: Intermittent| G[Lambda\ntrajectory-processor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|State Updates| H[DynamoDB\npatient-state]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|State Updates| H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Trajectory Metrics| I[Timestream\nvital-trajectories]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Trajectory Metrics| I
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Alert Triggers| J[Lambda\nalert-evaluator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Alert Triggers| J
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J -->|Fetch Context| H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J -->|Threshold Check| K{Alert Level?}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     K -->|Watch| L[DynamoDB\nUpdate Status]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     K -->|Alert/Alarm| M[SNS\nclinical-alerts]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M -->|Pager| N[Clinical Staff]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M -->|Dashboard| O[Unit Board]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M -->|EHR| P[In-Chart Notification]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style I fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style M fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Kinesis Data Streams, Kinesis Data Analytics (Flink), AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon Timestream, Amazon SNS, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `kinesis:PutRecord`, `kinesis:GetRecords`, `kinesisanalytics:*`, `lambda:InvokeFunction`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem`, `timestream:WriteRecords`, `timestream:Select`, `sns:Publish` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (vital signs are PHI; all services must be HIPAA-eligible) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | Kinesis: server-side encryption with KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); Timestream: encryption at rest (default); SNS: encrypted topics; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Flink application and Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for DynamoDB, Timestream, SNS, CloudWatch Logs. Interface endpoints for Kinesis. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. Critical for audit trail on alert generation and delivery. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Data Integration** | HL7v2 or FHIR interface to bedside monitor data, EHR vital sign documentation, and medication administration records. This is often the hardest prerequisite. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | MIMIC-III or MIMIC-IV (publicly available ICU datasets from MIT/PhysioNet) for development. Never use real patient data in dev environments. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Kinesis: ~$0.015/hr per shard (1 MB/s in). Lambda: negligible for intermittent vitals. Flink: ~$0.11/hr per KPU. DynamoDB: on-demand ~$1.25 per million writes. Timestream: ~$0.50/GB ingested. Total per patient-hour depends heavily on monitoring density. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams** | Ingests vital sign readings from all sources into an ordered, durable stream |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics** | Runs stateful Apache Flink application for continuous trajectory computation (ICU) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Processes intermittent vital sign events for floor patients; evaluates alert conditions |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores per-patient rolling state: baselines, current trajectory, alert history |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Timestream** | Stores full vital sign history and computed trajectory metrics for temporal queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SNS** | Routes clinical alerts to appropriate channels based on severity |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for all data stores and streams |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitors pipeline health, latency, error rates; alarms on processing delays |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Ingest vital sign event.** A new vital sign reading arrives from any source: a bedside monitor transmitting continuous waveforms, a nurse entering assessment data into the EHR, or a connected device reporting a measurement. The ingestion layer normalizes this into a standard event format and places it onto the streaming layer, keyed by patient ID to ensure per-patient ordering. The normalization step matters because different sources use different units (Celsius vs. Fahrenheit), different measurement types (invasive vs. non-invasive blood pressure), and different timestamp formats. Without normalization here, every downstream component would need to handle these variations. Skip this step and you get a stream of incompatible data formats that no trajectory logic can reliably process.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION ingest_vital_sign(source_event):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Normalize the incoming event into our standard format.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Different sources send data in wildly different shapes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // A bedside monitor sends numeric arrays every second.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // A nurse's EHR entry sends a single observation with free-text context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We need one consistent format downstream.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     normalized = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:      extract patient identifier from source_event,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         timestamp:       convert source timestamp to UTC ISO-8601,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         parameter:       standardize parameter name (e.g., "HR", "SBP", "DBP", "RR", "SpO2", "Temp"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         value:           numeric value in standard units (bpm, mmHg, breaths/min, %, Celsius),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         source_type:     "continuous_monitor" | "nursing_assessment" | "device",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         measurement_method: "invasive" | "non_invasive" | "manual",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence:      data quality indicator (1.0 for nurse-entered, variable for devices)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write to the streaming layer, partitioned by patient_id.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This guarantees all readings for a single patient arrive in order
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // at the same processing node.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write normalized to stream with partition_key = patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN normalized
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Retrieve and update patient state.** Before computing anything about a trajectory, we need to know what "normal" looks like for this patient right now. The patient state record holds rolling statistics computed from recent history: their median heart rate over the past 24 hours, the standard deviation of their blood pressure, their typical respiratory rate variability. On each new reading, we update these baselines using exponential moving averages, which weight recent readings more heavily while still incorporating longer-term history. This patient-specific baseline is what distinguishes "heart rate of 95 is concerning" (for a patient whose baseline is 68) from "heart rate of 95 is normal" (for a patient whose baseline is 92). Skip this step and you're comparing every patient against population norms, which generates massive false alert rates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION update_patient_state(vital_event):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Fetch this patient's current state from the state store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If no state exists (new admission), initialize with defaults.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state = fetch state for vital_event.patient_id from state_store
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF state is NULL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // New patient. Initialize with the first reading as a provisional baseline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // The baseline will stabilize after 4-6 hours of data collection.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:         vital_event.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             admitted_at:        vital_event.timestamp,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             baselines:          {},     // will be populated per-parameter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             trajectory:         {},     // will hold slope, acceleration per-parameter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             last_readings:      [],     // rolling window of recent values
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             alert_history:      [],     // track recent alerts to avoid flooding
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             baseline_stable:    false   // flag: not enough data yet for reliable alerts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     parameter = vital_event.parameter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     value     = vital_event.value
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update the rolling window for this parameter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Keep the last N readings (N depends on data density).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For continuous monitors: last 60 minutes of readings.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For intermittent assessments: last 10 readings.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     append {value: value, timestamp: vital_event.timestamp} to state.last_readings[parameter]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     trim state.last_readings[parameter] to max window size
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update baseline using exponential moving average (EMA).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Alpha controls responsiveness: smaller alpha = more stable baseline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We use alpha=0.05 for baselines (slow-moving) so short-term changes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // don't immediately shift what we consider "normal."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     alpha = 0.05
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF state.baselines[parameter] exists:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.baselines[parameter].mean = (1 - alpha) * state.baselines[parameter].mean + alpha * value
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Update rolling standard deviation estimate (Welford's method simplified)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         deviation = abs(value - state.baselines[parameter].mean)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.baselines[parameter].std = (1 - alpha) * state.baselines[parameter].std + alpha * deviation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.baselines[parameter] = { mean: value, std: 0.0 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check if we have enough data to consider baselines stable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Require at least 4 hours of data (or 10 intermittent readings).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     hours_since_admission = (vital_event.timestamp - state.admitted_at) in hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF hours_since_admission >= 4 AND NOT state.baseline_stable:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.baseline_stable = true
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Persist updated state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write state to state_store for vital_event.patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Compute trajectory features.** This is the core math. Given the rolling window of recent readings and the patient's established baseline, compute the trajectory: the slope (is it going up or down?), the acceleration (is the slope steepening?), the deviation from baseline (how far from normal?), and the variability (is the signal more erratic than usual?). These features capture the "shape" of the patient's recent physiological history. A simple linear regression over the recent window gives you the slope. The difference between the current slope and the slope from the prior window gives you acceleration. These are straightforward calculations, but they need to be robust to outliers and missing data. Skip this step and you have individual readings with no contextual meaning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION compute_trajectory(state, parameter):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     readings = state.last_readings[parameter]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF length(readings) < 3:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Not enough data to estimate a meaningful trajectory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN { slope: null, acceleration: null, deviation: null, variability: null }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute slope via simple linear regression over the recent window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // X = time offsets from first reading (in minutes).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Y = vital sign values.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     times  = [minutes_since(readings[0].timestamp, r.timestamp) for r in readings]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     values = [r.value for r in readings]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     slope = linear_regression_slope(times, values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // slope is in units-per-minute (e.g., bpm per minute for heart rate)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute acceleration: compare current slope to slope from the earlier half of the window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     midpoint = length(readings) / 2
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     early_slope = linear_regression_slope(times[0:midpoint], values[0:midpoint])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     late_slope  = linear_regression_slope(times[midpoint:], values[midpoint:])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     acceleration = late_slope - early_slope
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Positive acceleration = trend is steepening. Getting worse faster.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Deviation from patient baseline (in standard deviations).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_value = readings[last].value
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     baseline_mean = state.baselines[parameter].mean
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     baseline_std  = state.baselines[parameter].std
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF baseline_std > 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         deviation = (current_value - baseline_mean) / baseline_std
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         deviation = 0  // can't compute deviation without variability estimate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Variability: coefficient of variation over the recent window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // High variability can indicate instability even if the trend is flat.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     window_mean = mean(values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     window_std  = standard_deviation(values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     variability = window_std / window_mean IF window_mean > 0 ELSE 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     trajectory = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         parameter:    parameter,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         slope:        slope,           // units per minute
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         acceleration: acceleration,    // change in slope (second derivative)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         deviation:    deviation,       // standard deviations from patient baseline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         variability:  variability,     // coefficient of variation (instability indicator)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         current:      current_value,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         baseline:     baseline_mean,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         window_minutes: times[last]    // how much time this trajectory covers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN trajectory
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Multi-parameter correlation check.** Vital signs don't move independently. The body's compensatory mechanisms create correlated patterns. When multiple parameters move in a coordinated way that matches a known deterioration signature, that's much more concerning than any single parameter drifting. This step checks whether the current set of trajectories across all monitored parameters matches any known clinical pattern: the sepsis signature (rising HR + rising RR, then falling BP), the hemorrhage pattern (rising HR + falling BP + narrowing pulse pressure), the respiratory failure pattern (falling SpO2 + rising RR + rising HR). Pattern matching here dramatically improves specificity: instead of alerting on "heart rate trending up," you alert on "heart rate trending up in the context of respiratory rate also trending up, which matches the early sepsis signature." Skip this step and you're monitoring each vital sign in isolation, missing the inter-parameter signals that experienced clinicians recognize instantly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Known deterioration signatures. Each defines expected trajectory directions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // for multiple parameters that, when seen together, suggest a specific clinical concern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DETERIORATION_SIGNATURES = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "early_sepsis": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         required: { "HR": slope > 0, "RR": slope > 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         supporting: { "Temp": deviation > 1.5 OR deviation < -1.5, "SBP": slope < 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_required: 2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_supporting: 1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         severity: "alert",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         message: "Coordinated HR/RR rise with hemodynamic compromise consistent with early sepsis"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "hemorrhage": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         required: { "HR": slope > 0, "SBP": slope < 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         supporting: { "DBP": slope < 0, "RR": slope > 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_required: 2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_supporting: 1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         severity: "alarm",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         message: "Tachycardia with falling blood pressure suggests active hemorrhage"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "respiratory_failure": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         required: { "SpO2": slope < 0, "RR": slope > 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         supporting: { "HR": slope > 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_required: 2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_supporting: 0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         severity: "alert",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         message: "Falling oxygenation with compensatory tachypnea"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "cardiac_decompensation": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         required: { "HR": slope > 0, "SpO2": slope < 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         supporting: { "RR": slope > 0, "SBP": slope < 0 },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_required: 2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         min_supporting: 1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         severity: "alert",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         message: "Multi-parameter pattern consistent with cardiac decompensation"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION check_multi_parameter_patterns(all_trajectories):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     matched_patterns = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each pattern_name, signature in DETERIORATION_SIGNATURES:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         required_met = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         supporting_met = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each param, condition in signature.required:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF param in all_trajectories:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 traj = all_trajectories[param]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF evaluate_condition(traj, condition):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     required_met += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each param, condition in signature.supporting:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF param in all_trajectories:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 traj = all_trajectories[param]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF evaluate_condition(traj, condition):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     supporting_met += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF required_met >= signature.min_required AND supporting_met >= signature.min_supporting:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 pattern:  pattern_name,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 severity: signature.severity,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 message:  signature.message,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 evidence: { required_met, supporting_met, trajectories: all_trajectories }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             } to matched_patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN matched_patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Alert evaluation and suppression.** Not every trajectory anomaly should generate an alert. This step applies the intelligence layer: Should this alert fire? Has the patient recently received a medication that explains the trend? Was a similar alert generated in the last hour (avoid flooding)? Is the patient's baseline still stabilizing (first few hours of admission)? Is this a known post-procedure recovery pattern? The suppression logic is arguably more important than the detection logic. A system that fires correctly but too often is worse than a system that fires less often but is always meaningful. Clinical staff will tune out within days if your signal-to-noise ratio is poor. Skip this step and you'll achieve technically correct trajectory detection that nobody looks at.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION evaluate_alert(patient_state, trajectories, pattern_matches):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Suppression checks (any of these can block an alert)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 1. Baseline not yet stable (early admission period)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF NOT patient_state.baseline_stable:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN { action: "suppress", reason: "Baseline still stabilizing" }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 2. Recent alert for same pattern (cooldown period)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each recent_alert in patient_state.alert_history:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF recent_alert.pattern == pattern_matches[0].pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m            AND minutes_since(recent_alert.timestamp) < 60:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             RETURN { action: "suppress", reason: "Same alert within cooldown window" }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 3. Medication effect window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check if a medication administered in the last 2 hours has an expected
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // effect that explains the observed trajectory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recent_meds = fetch recent medications for patient_state.patient_id (last 2 hours)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each med in recent_meds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         expected_effects = lookup_expected_effects(med.medication_code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF current trajectory matches expected_effects:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             RETURN { action: "suppress", reason: "Expected medication effect: " + med.name }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 4. Artifact detection
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If a single reading caused a dramatic spike/drop that recovered within 2 minutes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // it's likely measurement artifact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each param, traj in trajectories:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF traj.variability > ARTIFACT_THRESHOLD AND traj.window_minutes < 2:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             RETURN { action: "suppress", reason: "Probable measurement artifact" }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // All suppression checks passed. Determine alert level.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF length(pattern_matches) > 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Multi-parameter pattern detected. Use the pattern's severity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         highest_severity = max severity across pattern_matches
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             action:   highest_severity,  // "alert" or "alarm"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patterns: pattern_matches,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             trajectories: trajectories
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // No multi-parameter pattern, but check individual parameter thresholds.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Single-parameter alerts require higher deviation to fire (reduce noise).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each param, traj in trajectories:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF abs(traj.deviation) > 3.0 AND abs(traj.slope) > SLOPE_THRESHOLD[param]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 action:   "watch",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 reason:   param + " deviating significantly with consistent slope",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 trajectories: trajectories
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN { action: "none" }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Persist trajectory metrics and route alerts.** The final step stores the computed trajectory data for historical analysis and research, then routes any active alerts to the appropriate clinical channels. Every trajectory computation is stored regardless of whether it triggered an alert, because retrospective analysis ("show me this patient's trajectory for the 12 hours before the code") is one of the most valuable use cases. Alert routing depends on severity: "watch" updates the patient's dashboard status, "alert" pages the assigned nurse, "alarm" triggers immediate clinical escalation. Each alert includes the trajectory visualization data so the clinician receiving it can see the pattern, not just a number.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION persist_and_route(patient_state, trajectories, alert_decision):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store trajectory metrics in time series database (always, regardless of alert)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each param, traj in trajectories:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         write to time_series_store:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:  patient_state.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timestamp:   current_time,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             parameter:   param,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             slope:       traj.slope,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             acceleration: traj.acceleration,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             deviation:   traj.deviation,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             variability: traj.variability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current:     traj.current,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             baseline:    traj.baseline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Route alert based on decision
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF alert_decision.action == "none" OR alert_decision.action == "suppress":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN  // nothing to route
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF alert_decision.action == "watch":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Update patient dashboard status. No active paging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update patient_state.status = "watching"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update unit_dashboard for patient_state.patient_id with trajectories
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF alert_decision.action == "alert":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Clinical alert: notify assigned nurse via preferred channel
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         alert_payload = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:   patient_state.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             severity:     "alert",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timestamp:    current_time,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             summary:      alert_decision.patterns[0].message,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             trajectories: format_for_display(trajectories),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             recommended:  "Assess patient. Consider increasing monitoring frequency."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         publish alert_payload to clinical_alerts_topic (filtered by unit + severity)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append alert_payload to patient_state.alert_history
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF alert_decision.action == "alarm":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // High-priority clinical alarm: immediate escalation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         alarm_payload = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:   patient_state.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             severity:     "alarm",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timestamp:    current_time,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             summary:      alert_decision.patterns[0].message,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             trajectories: format_for_display(trajectories),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             recommended:  "Immediate bedside assessment required. Consider rapid response activation."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         publish alarm_payload to clinical_alerts_topic (filtered by unit + severity)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append alarm_payload to patient_state.alert_history
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter12.07-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample trajectory alert output:**
